quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to create an array of integers named myArr containing values 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5. The size of the array is 5.
[!raw!]
{0} myArr[5] = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 {1};

Fill in the blanks to print to the screen the first and the last elements of an array with a size of 5.
[!raw!]
cout << arr[{0}] << endl;
cout << arr[{1}] << endl;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Initializing Arrays[/h1]

If you omit the size of the array, an array just big enough to hold the initialization is created. 
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" ]int b[] = {11, 45, 62, 70, 88};[/code]
This creates an identical array to the one created in the previous example.

Each element, or member, of the array has an [b]index[/b], which pinpoints the element's specific position.
The array's first member has the index of 0, the second has the index of 1. 
So, for the array [b]b[/b] that we declared above:  [img id="2459" width="100%"]
To access array elements, index the array name by placing the element's index in square brackets following the array name.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="218"]int b[] = {11, 45, 62, 70, 88};

cout << b[b][0][/b] << endl;
// Outputs 11

cout<< b[b][3][/b] << endl;
// Outputs 70[/code]
